Locked architectural decisions
1. Receipt is a portable trust artifact

The Receipt is generated from the Execution Trust Record.

It is designed for sharing and independent verification without exposing the complete trust record.

2. One Receipt per terminal Execution

A Receipt is issued only after an Execution reaches a terminal state:

COMPLETED
FAILED

No Receipt exists while an Execution is still PROCESSING.

3. Receipt is immutable

Once issued:

it cannot be modified;
it cannot be regenerated with different contents;
it permanently represents the Execution Trust Record at the time of issuance.
4. Cryptographic integrity

Every Receipt contains:

executionTrustRecordHash
signature
keyId
algorithm

These fields enable independent verification without requiring access to Parmana.

5. Receipt is not the source of truth

The canonical source of truth remains the Execution Trust Record.

The Receipt is a signed, portable representation of that record.

Canonical Principle (Locked)

A Receipt is a cryptographically signed, portable proof of execution.

It represents the Execution Trust Record at a specific point in time and enables independent verification while preserving the Execution Trust Record as the authoritative source of truth.

